<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec32-PropertiesDeterminants" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Properties of Determinants</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we will see how to compute the determinant of a matrix inverse, which also tells us about the invertibility of a matrix. 
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Apply the multiplicative property of determinants
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            determine whether a matrix is invertible by computing its determinant
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

    <p>
      The most important theorem about determinants is this one: 
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-DeterminantsProducts">
      <title>Determinants and Products</title>
      <statement>
          <p>
              Suppose <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices. 
              Then
              <md>
                  \det (AB) = \det A \det B
              </md>
              That is, the determinant of the product is the product of the determinants. 
          </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      And one consequence of this is the following Lemma: 
    </p>

    <lemma xml:id="lem-DeterminantsInverses">
      <statement>
          <p>
              Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix, then <m>\det A = 0</m> if and only if <m>A</m> has <alert>no</alert> inverse (hence <m>A</m> is not invertible). 
          </p>
      </statement>
    </lemma>

    <example>
      <p>
          We know that
          <md>
              \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -2 \\ -9 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ -9 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp \frac{-2}{5} \\ 0 \amp \frac{7}{5} \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
          We can calculate the determinant of all three matrices and quickly verify that
          <md>
              \begin{vmatrix} 5 \amp -2 \\ -9 \amp 5 \end{vmatrix} = \begin{vmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ -9 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp \frac{-2}{5} \\ 0 \amp \frac{7}{5} \end{vmatrix}
          </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      If we know that <m>A</m> is invertible, then we can use the above theorem to compute the determinant of the inverse of <m>A</m>. 
      Since <m>AA^{-1} = I</m>, we have
      <md>
      <mrow> \det (AA^{-1}) \amp= \det I </mrow>
        <mrow> \implies \qquad \det A \det A^{-1} \amp= 1 </mrow>
          <mrow>\implies\qquad \qquad  \det A^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{\det A} </mrow>
      </md>
      Hence, <m>\det\lp A^{-1} \rp = \dfrac{1}{\det A}</m>. 
      We can make it a theorem!
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-InverseDeterminant">
      <title>Determinants and Inverses</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> <alert>invertible</alert> matrix. 
          Then
          <md>
            \det A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det A}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      The next theorem tells us about the determinants and transpose. 
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-TransposeDeterminant">
      <title>Determinants and Transpose</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix. 
          Then
          <md>
            \det A^T = \det A
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      What the theorem tells us is that the determinant of any square matrix is the same as the determinant of its transpose. 
    </p>

    <proof>
      <title>Proof using Elementary Matrices... </title>
      <p>
        First, let's make sure this is true for elementary matrices. 
        <ol marker="Type 1">
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>E</m> is obtained by swapping two rows on <m>I</m>, then <m>E^T</m> is obtained by swapping the corresponding columns of <m>I</m>. 
              In each case, the determinant is <m>-1</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>E</m> is obtained by multiplying a row of <m>I</m> by a constant, then notice that <m>E^T = E</m>. 
              So certainly <m>E^T</m> and <m>E</m> have the same determinant in this case (it is whatever the constant is). 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>E</m> is obtained by adding a multiple of a row of <m>I</m> to another row of <m>I</m>. 
              The transpose could be obtained the same way (reversing the two rows). 
              Or we we could do it by doing the same operation on the corresponding columns of <m>I</m>. 
              In any case, the determinant of <m>E</m> and <m>E^T</m> are both <m>1</m> because those operations do not change the determinant of <m>I</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        So the result holds for elementary matrices. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Now let's do the proof for any <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>A</m> is not invertible, then neither is <m>A^T</m>. 
        <note>
          <title>Hmm why is that? </title> 
          
          <p>
            If <m>A^T B = I</m>, then <m>B^T A = I^T = I</m>. 
            So we would have an inverse for <m>A</m> if we had one for <m>A^T</m>. 
          </p>
        </note>

        So if <m>\det A = 0</m>, then <m>\det A^T = 0</m> as well. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Suppose <m>\det A \neq 0</m>, then <m>A</m> is invertible and can be written as a product of elementary matrices. 
        Let's say
        <md>
          A = E_1 E_2 \ldots E_k
        </md>
        Then by this theorem <xref ref="thm-RulesMatrixMultiplication"/>, we know that
        <md>
          A^T = E_K^T \ldots E_2^T E_1^T
        </md>
        Therefore, 
        <md>
          <mrow>\det A^T \amp= \det \lp E_K^T \ldots E_2^T E_1^T \rp </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \det E_k^T \, \ldots \, \det E_2^T \, \det E_1^T </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \det E_k \, \ldots \, \det E_2 \, \det E_1 </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \det E_1 \, \det E_2 \, \ldots \, \det E_K </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \det \lp E_1 E_2 \ldots E_k \rp </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \det A </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </proof>

    <proof>
      <title>Proof Idea using Mathematical Induction... </title>
      <p>
        This proof (idea) is easier but uses a proof technique most MTH 261 students would not be familiar with called <alert>Mathematical Induction</alert>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        The idea in this case is that the theory is easily verified for <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices: 
        <ul marker="">
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, we can see that 
              <md>
                \det A = ad - bc
              </md>
              Since <m>A^T = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp c \\ b \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, we can verify that
              <md>
                \det A^T = ad - bc
              </md>
              Same thing. 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        Now suppose we were working with a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. 
        Then the first row of <m>A</m> becomes the first column of <m>A^T</m>. 
        So if we calculate the determinant using the cofactor method and expand on the first row of <m>A</m> and the first column of <m>A^T</m>, we will see that we get the same thing <em>except</em> each of the little <m>2 \times 2</m> determinants has been transposed when we are working with <m>A^T</m>. 
        And since we know from the <m>2 \times 2</m> case that these are the same, it follows that we get the same answer for <m>\det A</m> and <m>\det A^T</m> in the <m>3 \times 3</m> case as well. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Then we can repeat that same strategy for <m>4 \times 4</m> and so on and so on forever and ever... 
      </p>
    </proof>

    <p>
      <alert>In the 4th lab report, you will explore an application of the determinant, which is to extend the inverse formula back in <xref ref="sec22-InverseMatrix"/>using determinants and adjugates. </alert>
    </p>

</section>